Very interesting. It needs to be asked whether the Yoga class dedicated to the rising of the soul is considered by its practitioners as exercise devoid of spiritual meaning. I would guess otherwise. 
I wrote a bit about Yoga&#039;s adoption in the west in Ma&#039;ariv a few months ago, translated into English here: http://tomerpersicoenglish.wordpress.com/2013/04/25/spirituality-athletics-yoga-pizza/

&lt;blockquote&gt;At the end of February this year a woman named Ronnie Abramson went to a yoga class. Amidst the positions and stretching exercises she was dismayed to realize that the instructor was telling her about the month of Adar, the Book of Esther, the feast of Purim and the Almighty. Abramson, who sought only a standard yoga class, felt that she was not getting what she paid for, and was in fact suffering a minor assault of religious coercion. She wrote a short account of the experience for ‘Haaretz’ in which she asks that secular folks be allowed to practice yoga without being forced to listen to religious sermons.&lt;/blockquote&gt;
